to get approved,

00:15:29.728 --> 00:15:32.231
by which point, homeowner's have
probably had to

00:15:32.331 --> 00:15:34.766
rebuild their house at the
government's expense

00:15:35.033 --> 00:15:36.835
and it may have
already flooded again.

00:15:37.202 --> 00:15:38.770
So, essentially,
a government program

00:15:38.871 --> 00:15:41.173
that was supposed to help people
in flooded homes

00:15:41.273 --> 00:15:44.042
is sometimes trapping them
inside them indefinitely.

00:15:44.343 --> 00:15:46.845
And trapping people in
structurally-unsound homes

00:15:47.079 --> 00:15:48.580
isn't what
the government is for,

00:15:48.680 --> 00:15:50.615
it's what buying
the beach is for.

00:15:50.715 --> 00:15:51.617
(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

00:15:51.717 --> 00:15:54.719
No, there just has to be
a better way here,

00:15:54.820 --> 00:15:56.822
and there are some key
things that we can do

00:15:56.922 --> 00:15:57.756
to improve this program.

00:15:57.856 --> 00:15:59.291
We can do things like
means-test it

00:15:59.524 --> 00:16:02.194
and eventually get rid
of discounts for second homes

00:16:02.294 --> 00:16:04.529
and gradually increase
the insurance rates

00:16:04.629 --> 00:16:07.132
on some properties so that they
reflect actual risk.

00:16:07.433 --> 00:16:09.734
Unfortunately, the last time
that Congress tried

00:16:09.834 --> 00:16:11.270
a major reform of the NFIP

00:16:11.370 --> 00:16:13.539
with the Biggert-Waters Act
of 2012,

00:16:13.806 --> 00:16:16.841
the result was that many
people's rates skyrocketed

00:16:16.941 --> 00:16:20.112
overnight and politicians were
so spooked by angry constituents

00:16:20.212 --> 00:16:23.148
